# Operational Gotchas

Non-obvious facts about this codebase that have caused agent mistakes in past sessions.
Apply this rule when touching PRISMA, run history, export, or production serving.

## PRISMA Checklist Filename
The API reads `doc_manuscript.md` from the run directory, NOT `manuscript.md`.
If the PRISMA checklist card shows "data not available", check that `doc_manuscript.md` exists.

## Historical Run Endpoints
PRISMA and results endpoints require the run to be registered in `_active_runs` in memory.
After a server restart, historical runs are NOT in `_active_runs`.
Use `POST /api/history/attach` to re-register a completed run before calling any results or PRISMA APIs.
The PRISMA checklist endpoint falls back to `workflows_registry.db` automatically when the run_id
is not in `_active_runs` -- supports both short run_ids and workflow_ids (wf-XXXXXXXX format).

## Production Build
The production URL (`https://litreview.parthchandak.info`) serves `frontend/dist/` -- NOT the Vite dev server.
Frontend code changes are invisible in production until you run `cd frontend && pnpm build`.
The Vite dev server on localhost:5173 picks up changes automatically.

## Backend Module Reload
Python loads all modules at startup. Any change to `src/` is invisible until `pm2 restart litreview-api`.
The running process uses the pre-edit bytecode even after the file is saved.

## INSERT OR REPLACE Is Destructive
SQLite `INSERT OR REPLACE` performs DELETE + INSERT. With `PRAGMA foreign_keys = ON`
the DELETE step fails if child tables reference the row. This was the root cause of
all "FOREIGN KEY constraint failed" errors on resume. Always use
`INSERT ... ON CONFLICT(pk) DO UPDATE SET ...` instead. See sqlite-patterns-auto.mdc.

## INSERT OR IGNORE Does Not Suppress FK Violations
SQLite `OR IGNORE` only suppresses UNIQUE, NOT NULL, and CHECK constraint errors.
Foreign key violations always raise IntegrityError regardless of the conflict clause.
When bulk-inserting rows with FK references, verify the parent rows exist first.

## CLI Resume vs Web Resume
When the API is running, `uv run python -m src.main resume` delegates to POST /api/history/resume
so the frontend shows live progress. If the API is down, the CLI runs locally (no live UI).
Use `--no-api` to force local run even when the API is up. Local-only runs appear in RECENT
but without heartbeat they may show as "stale" after 5 min.

## Citation Ledger: Numeric [N] Keys Are Valid
The final `doc_manuscript.md` uses numbered citations [1], [2], ... after
`convert_to_numbered_citations()` replaces author-year citekeys. The citation
ledger's `validate_manuscript()` now accepts numeric keys as valid when N is
in [1, count_of_known_citations]. This was a historical source of false
`citation_lineage_valid=false` in `run_summary.json`.

## PRISMA automation_excluded vs "other"
`PRISMACounts.automation_excluded` tracks records removed by BM25/keyword
pre-filter BEFORE LLM screening. In the PRISMA flow diagram this maps to
"Removed before screening: Automation tools (n=X)" -- NOT to "other_removed".
The gap `records_after_dedup - records_screened` is now captured explicitly
in this field (backfilled to 0 for older PRISMACounts objects).
Always check this field when PRISMA math appears incorrect.

## Methodology References Pre-Registered in Citations Table
`register_methodology_citations()` in `src/writing/orchestration.py` pre-registers
5 fixed methodology papers (PRISMA 2020 Page2021, RoB 2 Sterne2019, ROBINS-I Sterne2016,
GRADE Guyatt2011, Cohen1960) into the citations table before writing starts.
These citekeys appear in the catalog and are in `valid_citekeys`, so the writing LLM
can cite them in the Methods section. They are included in the final numbered reference list.

## PRISMA Full-Text Count Uses Actual Fulltext Stage
`build_prisma_counts()` in `src/prisma/diagram.py` now checks `_reports_assessed_raw`
from `dual_screening_results`. When `_reports_assessed_raw > included_total`, real
full-text exclusions exist and those counts are used for PRISMA accuracy. The old
behavior (hardcode `reports_assessed = included_total`) silently dropped exclusions
that occurred at the fulltext screening stage.

## CROSS_SECTIONAL Studies Route to CASP, Not ROBINS-I
`StudyRouter.route_tool()` in `src/quality/study_router.py` routes `CROSS_SECTIONAL`
to `casp` (CASP cohort/cross-sectional checklist). ROBINS-I requires a defined
intervention and comparator group; cross-sectional surveys lack this structure.
Only NON_RANDOMIZED, COHORT, and CASE_CONTROL route to ROBINS-I.

## Reviewer Language Is Neutral (No AI/Human Qualifier)
`screening_method_description` in `WritingGroundingData` uses "Two independent reviewers"
with no AI or human qualifier. The TRANSPARENCY RULE in `format_grounding_block()` enforces
this: do NOT specify whether reviewers were human or AI in any section prompt.
Prompt instructions that say "AI-assisted screening" in this repo are stale -- the
canonical source of truth is `context_builder.py` (`format_grounding_block`) and `sections.py` lines ~184-189.

## PubMed Search Override Phrase Sensitivity (Critical for Recall)
The PubMed query is built from `search_overrides.pubmed` in `config/review.yaml`.
Exact-phrase requirements in the second AND group kill recall dramatically:
- `"[setting phrase]"[Title/Abstract]` (2-word exact phrase) returns 10-50x fewer records
  than `"[setting word]"[Title/Abstract]` (single word) for the same topic
Always use single-word OR terms in the setting group, never multi-word exact phrases.
Also avoid narrow secondary MeSH terms in the AND group -- many papers on the target topic
are not indexed under them, causing silent exclusions. The auto-generated fallback query
(when no override is set) may produce better recall than a poorly crafted override. If a run
returns fewer papers from PubMed than a prior run with the same topic, compare the actual
queries in `doc_search_strategies_appendix.md`.

## OpenAlex `is_core:true` Filter Was Removed (March 2026)
The `is_core:true` filter was removed from `src/search/openalex.py`. It restricted results
to CWTS Core-list journals (Scopus/WoS equivalent), causing OpenAlex to return very few
records for specialized or niche topics regardless of query. The correct approach is:
search broadly (without the core filter), then let the dual-LLM screeners apply inclusion
criteria to eliminate low-quality papers. Remaining filters (`type:article`,
`primary_location.source.type:journal`, `is_retracted:false`) are sufficient for quality.
Do NOT add `is_core:true` back -- it is an intentional removal to support broad-search/
tight-screen methodology. `per_database_limits.openalex` in `settings.yaml` is 1000 (not 500).
The `limits_applied` metadata string in the `SearchResult` now correctly reflects the active
filters (`max_results,type=article,source_type=journal,is_retracted=false`).

## `build_boolean_query` Uses Keywords Only (Not PICO Descriptions)
`build_boolean_query()` in `src/search/strategy.py` uses ONLY `config.keywords`. It does
NOT include `config.pico.intervention` or `config.pico.outcome`. PICO descriptions are
multi-sentence text that never appears verbatim in papers -- adding them produces zero-result
ClinicalTrials.gov queries and noisy results elsewhere. Do NOT add PICO description strings
back to the `keyword_terms` list. Similarly, `short_query` uses `" ".join(config.keywords[:8])`.

## ClinicalTrials.gov Uses OR-Joined Keywords (Not PICO Sentences)
`clinicaltrials_gov` has its own case in `build_database_query()`:
`" OR ".join(f'"{k}"' for k in config.keywords[:12])`.
Previously it fell through to `return base` (which included full PICO sentences) and always
returned 0 results. Use `search_overrides.clinicaltrials_gov` in `config/review.yaml` to
provide a hand-crafted query; the fallback uses the top 12 keywords quoted with OR.

## WoS Quota Exhaustion Surfaces as "FAILED" (Not Silent 0-Result Success)
WoS Starter API has a 300 req/day free limit. After exhausting retries on 429 errors,
`WebOfScienceConnector.search()` raises `RuntimeError`. The coordinator catches this and
marks WoS as "failed" in the activity log SSE event. If you see "SEARCH FAILED: wos...",
the API key quota is exhausted for the day. Wait 24h or check the Clarivate dev portal.

## "insufficient_data" Is a Full-Text-Only Exclusion Reason
The dual screener may produce `insufficient_data` as an exclusion reason. This is only
methodologically valid at the full-text screening stage (paper lacks empirical data).
At the title/abstract stage, `insufficient_data` is incorrect -- papers that lack data in
their abstract may still contain empirical data in the full text. If you see many
`insufficient_data` exclusions at title/abstract stage in the screening log, the LLM
reviewer is likely over-applying this reason to borderline records. The correct title/abstract
reasons are: `wrong_population`, `wrong_intervention`, `wrong_outcome`, `wrong_setting`,
`wrong_study_design`, or `low_relevance_score`.

## Per-Run Logging Uses Per-File-Handle Dict (Fixed)
`configure_run_logging()` in `src/utils/structured_log.py` now uses a
`_file_handles: dict[str, TextIO]` keyed by `log_dir`. Each run gets its own `app.jsonl`
file handle regardless of how many sequential runs the API process serves. The old
`_configured` single-flag bug (all runs writing to the first run's log dir) is gone.
`load_events_from_jsonl()` also skips non-dict JSON values defensively.

## Citation-Chased Papers Are Screened In The Same Run (Fixed)
`ScreeningNode` in `src/orchestration/workflow.py` now screens citation-chased papers
immediately after they are fetched. After `chase_citations_to_search_results()` returns,
the code runs the dual screener on `new_papers` (title/abstract then fulltext), updates
`state.deduped_papers` and `state.included_papers` accordingly, and emits
`chased_included` in the `citation_chasing` phase-done event. Chased papers contribute
proper rows to `dual_screening_results` and PRISMA math is accurate. The
`screen_batch` resume-skip logic ensures idempotency if the run is interrupted and resumed.

## HITL Approval Now Propagates Overrides Fully (Fixed)
`POST /api/run/{run_id}/approve-screening` now upserts each human override into
`screening_decisions` (reviewer_type='human_override') and updates `dual_screening_results`
(`final_decision`). After the HITL loop completes, `HumanReviewCheckpointNode` reloads
`state.included_papers` from the DB so extraction sees the corrected inclusion set.
Resume also re-enters the HITL gate if the registry status is `awaiting_review`.

## Screening Summary API Uses `reason` (Not `rationale`)
`GET /api/run/{run_id}/screening-summary` selects `sd.reason` (the correct column name).
The frontend `ScreeningReviewView.tsx` also reads `paper.reason` (not `paper.rationale`).
Both sides are aligned. If you see a blank "AI Rationale" panel in the HITL tab on an
older install, the page may be reading a stale JS bundle -- run `pnpm build`.

## CASP And MMAT Assessments Are Now Persisted (Fixed)
`src/db/schema.sql` now has `casp_assessments` and `mmat_assessments` tables with
`PRIMARY KEY (workflow_id, paper_id)`. `src/db/repositories.py` has `save_casp_assessment()`
and `save_mmat_assessment()` using ON CONFLICT upsert. `ExtractionQualityNode` calls
these at all 4 call sites (main loop + quality-retry loop for each type). On resume,
already-assessed CASP/MMAT papers are skipped correctly.

## GRADE Now Aggregates Per-Outcome Across All Papers (Fixed)
`ExtractionQualityNode` now accumulates `(record, rob_assessment, outcome_name)` tuples
during the per-paper loop, then after both loops it groups by `outcome_name` and calls
`grade.assess_from_rob()` (or `assess_outcome()` for CASP/MMAT studies) once per unique
outcome with ALL relevant papers as `number_of_studies`. `save_grade_assessment()` is called
once per outcome — the old per-paper overwrite bug is gone.

## search_date In Manuscript Uses Actual Search Date (Fixed)
`WritingNode` in `src/orchestration/workflow.py` now queries `MAX(search_date)` from
the `search_results` table and passes the result to `build_writing_grounding()`.
The manuscript Methods section and PRISMA dates now reflect when the search was
actually run rather than always defaulting to the current calendar year.

## Phase-4 Citation Lineage Gate Removed (Fixed)
The stub `run_citation_lineage_gate(unresolved_items=0)` call was removed from
`ExtractionQualityNode`. No manuscript exists at phase-4 (writing happens later in
`WritingNode`), so there is nothing to validate at that point. Real citation lineage
validation happens in `FinalizeNode` (lines ~2714-2738) using the actual assembled
manuscript text and the `CitationLedger`. That check is the authoritative gate and
respects `citation_lineage.block_export_on_unresolved` from `settings.yaml`.

## PM2 Process Names Are litreview-api / litreview-ui / litreview-tunnel
The ecosystem.config.js defines processes as `litreview-api`, `litreview-ui`, and
`litreview-tunnel`. PM2 shorthand aliases like `api` or `ui` do NOT work unless
you explicitly configured them. Always use the full process names:
  pm2 logs litreview-api
  pm2 restart litreview-api
  pm2 restart litreview-ui

## Background SR Citekeys Must Be ASCII (No Accented Characters)
`register_background_sr_citations()` in `src/writing/orchestration.py` builds citekeys
as `{first_surname}{year}SR`. Author surnames with accented characters (e.g. "Perez"
from "Perez-Encinas") produce citekeys like `[Perez-Encinas2020SR]` that the citation
ledger regex `[A-Za-z0-9_:-]+` cannot match -- they appear verbatim and unresolved in
the final manuscript. The fix is already applied: `unicodedata.normalize("NFD", surname)`
strips accents before building the citekey. Do NOT remove this normalization.

## `WritingGroundingData` Has Three Config-Derived Fields (Not DB-Derived)
`search_eligibility_window`, `fulltext_retrieved_count`/`fulltext_total_count`, and
`author_name` are populated by `build_writing_grounding()` from `review_config` and
`extraction_records`, NOT from the database or PRISMA counts directly:
- `search_eligibility_window`: computed from `review_config.date_range_start`/`date_range_end`
  (e.g. "2000-2026"). DISTINCT from `year_range` (min-max of included papers). The LLM is
  instructed to report the eligibility window in Methods, not the included-papers year range.
- `fulltext_retrieved_count`: count of extraction_records where `extraction_source != "text"`
  (i.e. NOT abstract-only). `"text"` and `"heuristic"` are abstract-only; all other values
  indicate actual full-text retrieval.
- `author_name`: read from `review_config.author_name`; defaults to "Corresponding Author"
  when blank. Used in CRediT statement. Set `author_name:` in `config/review.yaml` to
  populate correctly.

## Setup Form Pre-fills API Keys From Server .env
`GET /api/config/env-keys` returns API keys already set in the server's .env file.
`SetupView.tsx` calls this on mount and backfills any empty form fields (localStorage
values always take priority; server values only fill blanks). This means users running
on the local server don't need to retype keys already configured in `.env`. Do NOT
treat missing localStorage keys as a hard error -- the env-keys endpoint is the fallback.

## PDFRetriever.retrieve() Also Works On URL-Only Papers
`PDFRetriever.retrieve()` in `src/search/pdf_retrieval.py` now attempts retrieval
when `paper.url` is set even if `paper.doi` is None. `PDFRetrievalResult` also carries
`pdf_bytes` and `source` fields (source strings include `url_direct_pdf`, `url_direct_text`,
`landing_page`, `landing_page_pdf` variants). `ReferencesView.tsx` SourceBadge handles
all these source strings. Do NOT assume `pdf_bytes` requires a DOI.

## Rate Limiter Now Covers All Major LLM Call Sites
`provider.reserve_call_slot(agent_name)` is now called before EVERY pro/flash LLM call:
- `extractor.py` → reserve "extraction" before each study LLM extraction
- `writing/orchestration.py` → reserve "writing" before each section write
- `workflow.py` → reserve "humanizer" before each humanize pass
- `rob2.py`, `robins_i.py`, `casp.py`, `mmat.py` → reserve "quality_assessment" each
If you add a new LLM-calling module, always add a `reserve_call_slot()` call to prevent
silent quota exhaustion for pro-tier models like Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview.

## All LLM Models Are Centralized In config/settings.yaml
No Gemini model string is hardcoded anywhere in src/. All 18 agent keys +
rag.embed_model/hyde_model/reranker_model + extraction.pdf_vision_model live in
`config/settings.yaml`. Module fallbacks use `src.llm.model_fallback.get_fallback_model(tier)`
which reads settings.yaml first and only falls back to _TIER_LAST_RESORT constants when YAML
cannot be parsed. To change any model, edit settings.yaml only -- no Python edits needed.
The 18 agent keys are: screening_reviewer_a/b, screening_adjudicator, batch_screener,
search, extraction, quality_assessment, study_type_detection, writing, abstract_generation,
humanizer, contradiction_resolver, criteria_refinement, table_extraction,
config_generation, concept_diagrams, narrative, style_extraction.
NOTE: naturalness_scorer was removed from settings.yaml when its dead-code module was deleted.
style_extraction remains in settings.yaml but the style_extractor module returns empty patterns
and prepare_writing_context() no longer uses it -- effectively dead in the pipeline.

## Batch LLM Pre-Ranker Sits Between BM25 and Dual-Reviewer
`src/screening/batch_ranker.py` implements a batch scoring step that fires after BM25
ranking and before the full dual-reviewer LLM pass. It scores papers in batches using
the `batch_screener` agent (settings.yaml). Papers scoring below `batch_screen_threshold`
(0.35, from the `screening:` section of settings.yaml) are auto-excluded as `batch_screened_low` and emitted via the
`batch_screen_done` SSE event (visible in the FUNNEL log line). Only papers above the
threshold proceed to the dual-reviewer. The funnel display shows "N to dual-reviewer"
and "M auto-excluded (score < X%)" for this stage. If batch_ranker raises an exception,
ScreeningNode falls back to passing ALL BM25-ranked papers to the dual-reviewer.

## Resume May Skip Phases Due To Stale Zero-Result Checkpoint
`resume.py` uses `from_phase` checkpoints. If a phase completes but produces 0 results
(e.g. writing phase saves `sections: 0`), resume treats the checkpoint as valid and skips
re-running the phase -- jumping straight to the next one. To force re-execution: manually
delete the phase checkpoint row from `checkpoints` table in `runtime.db` and reset the
run status to `running`. This was the root cause of empty manuscripts after model quota
exhaustion mid-run: the writing phase saved a zero-section checkpoint, causing all subsequent
resumes to skip writing entirely.

## tests/conftest.py Uses load_dotenv(override=True) for API Keys
`tests/conftest.py` (project root) calls `load_dotenv(override=True)` at session start.
`override=True` is intentional: it ensures the `.env` file's API key values take precedence
over any stale/invalid key already exported in the shell environment (e.g. an expired
`GOOGLE_API_KEY` set in `.zshrc`). The production config loader uses the default
`load_dotenv()` (no override) -- the override is test-only. If LLM-dependent integration
tests are skipping or failing with auth errors, check whether `GOOGLE_API_KEY` in the
shell differs from the one in `.env`.

## `search_eligibility_window` vs `year_range` Are Different Things
`WritingGroundingData.year_range` = "2016-2025" (min-max publication years of included papers).
`WritingGroundingData.search_eligibility_window` = "2000-2026" (protocol date range from YAML).
The LLM MUST use the eligibility window for the Methods section date statement and the
year range only when describing the characteristics of included studies. Confusing them
was the root cause of the audit finding "Methods says 2016-2025 but config says 2000-2026".

## CITATION CATALOG Block Enforces Correct Citekeys In Writing LLM
`format_grounding_block()` in `src/writing/context_builder.py` injects a "CITATION CATALOG"
block listing every exact citekey with a title snippet. The writing LLM is instructed to use
ONLY the citekeys in this catalog. Without this block, LLMs invent citekeys like [Castelao2015]
that do not match the registered key (e.g. Ezequiel2015), causing unresolved citations and a
reference list with only 6 entries. A second repair pass in `src/writing/citation_grounding.py`
(`repair_hallucinated_citekeys()`) fuzzy-matches remaining unknown citekeys against the citations
table by author_token + year before falling back to [CITATION_NEEDED]. Both safeguards are needed
because the catalog prompt alone does not eliminate all hallucinations.

## Kappa Restored From event_log On Resume (Not From State)
`state.cohens_kappa` is not persisted to the database. On resume, it starts as None, which causes
`format_grounding_block()` to emit "kappa NOT available" even when kappa was computed in the
original run. Fix: `src/orchestration/resume.py` reads the `phase_done` event with
`phase='screening_calibration'` from `event_log` and restores `state.cohens_kappa`,
`state.kappa_stage`, and `state.kappa_n`. If you add any other transient state fields that
affect manuscript content, add the same restore pattern to `resume.py`.

## Sidebar "Papers Included" Uses phase_done Event Count (Not dual_screening_results)
`_fetch_run_stats()` in `src/web/app.py` now derives `papers_included` from the
`phase_done` SSE event where `phase='phase_3_screening'` rather than counting rows in
`dual_screening_results WHERE final_decision='include'`. The old query over-counted because
it included abstract-stage "include" decisions for papers later excluded at full-text.
The event-based count matches the top progress bar. A fallback query (most-advanced-stage
deduplication) is used when the phase_done event is absent (in-progress runs).

## doc_manuscript.tex and references.bib Are First-Class Run Artifacts
`FinalizeNode` in `src/orchestration/workflow.py` now generates `doc_manuscript.tex` and
`references.bib` directly into the run directory (alongside `doc_manuscript.md`) as
first-class artifacts -- no separate POST /export call required. Both are also
pre-registered in `StartNode` so their paths appear in artifact lists even before finalize.
The submission packager still produces its own `manuscript.tex` inside `submission/`
(with `\includegraphics` for figures); the run-dir `.tex` is the same content without
a bundled figures/ directory. Both are valid IEEE LaTeX -- the run-dir copy is for
single-file inspection; the `submission/` copy is for pdflatex compilation.

## records_after_deduplication Is Pre-Computed (LLM Must Not Subtract)
`WritingGroundingData.records_after_deduplication` is explicitly pre-computed as
`total_identified - duplicates_removed` and injected into the grounding block verbatim.
`format_grounding_block()` includes a CRITICAL instruction telling the LLM to use this
value as-is and NOT to compute it by subtraction.
Root cause that prompted this fix: LLM computed 1908 - 24 = 1882 (wrong) instead of 1884.
The same pattern applies to `records_excluded_screening` (pre-computed as
`total_screened - fulltext_assessed`). Never remove these fields or rely on the LLM to
perform PRISMA arithmetic -- LLM arithmetic on injected grounding counts is unreliable.

## `_escape_latex()` Uses pylatexenc Fallback -- Do Not Add Manual Accented-Char Entries
`_escape_latex()` in `src/export/ieee_latex.py` uses a 7-entry targeted typographic table
(em-dash, en-dash, smart quotes, non-breaking hyphen) for IEEEtran-preferred syntax,
then `pylatexenc.latexencode.UnicodeToLatexEncoder` as a generic Unicode->LaTeX fallback
(Step 5), and finally a last-resort guard replacing any remaining non-ASCII with `[?]` (Step 6).
Do NOT add individual accented-char mappings (e.g. `a -> \~{a}`) -- pylatexenc handles all of
them generically. `\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}`, `\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}`, and
`\usepackage{textcomp}` are all in the generated preamble so common accented chars work
natively. The property-based test `test_escape_latex_always_ascii_output` in
`tests/unit/test_export.py` uses `hypothesis` to assert the invariant for arbitrary Unicode.

## Kappa nan Is Guarded In context_builder.py (Not Propagated to LLM)
`format_grounding_block()` in `src/writing/context_builder.py` uses `math.isnan()` to guard
`cohens_kappa` before formatting. If `cohens_kappa` is `nan` (e.g. N=1, single-class input
to `cohen_kappa_score()`), the grounding block emits "not calculable (N=X)" instead of
the raw `nan` value. Do NOT remove this guard -- propagating `nan` into an LLM prompt
produces unreliable Methods section text and triggered schema validation errors in past runs.

## `save_cost_record()` Takes CostRecord Directly (No workflow_id Argument)
`WorkflowRepository.save_cost_record(self, record: CostRecord)` takes exactly ONE argument
beyond `self` -- the CostRecord object. There is NO workflow_id parameter. The cost_records
table has no workflow_id column. Calling `save_cost_record(workflow_id, CostRecord(...))` passes
workflow_id as the record and CostRecord as a phantom third positional arg, raising a silent
TypeError (swallowed by try/except). This caused embedding cost records to silently not save
in EmbeddingNode. Correct usage:
```python
await repo.save_cost_record(CostRecord(model=..., phase=..., tokens_in=..., ...))
```
